  "pmid": "29209312",
  "doi": "10.3389/fimmu.2017.01503",
  "title": "Dual Molecular Mechanisms Govern Escape at Immunodominant HLA A2-Restricted HIV Epitope.",
  "journal": "Frontiers in immunology",
  "year": 2017,
  "authors": "Cole DK, Fuller A, Dolton G, Zervoudi E, Legut M, Miles K, Blanchfield L, Madura F, Holland CJ, Bulek AM, Bridgeman JS, Miles JJ, Schauenburg AJA, Beck K, Evavold BD, Rizkallah PJ, Sewell AK."
 },
 "executive_summary": "The study characterizes escape mechanisms at the SL9 epitope, an immunodominant HLA-A2\u2013restricted HIV p17 Gag peptide recognized by cytotoxic T lymphocytes, by comparing TCR binding to the wild-type SLYNTVATL peptide and a triple-mutant escape variant (SLFNTIAVL) that accumulates during HIV infection. Through crystal structure of the TCR\u2013peptide\u2013HLA complex, the authors reveal that immune escape operates primarily through destabilization of peptide\u2013HLA binding and reduction of peptide surface density, rather than through direct loss of TCR engagement as previously hypothesized. Position 4 asparagine emerges as the main TCR contact residue, and solvent-exposed mutations do not abrogate recognition but instead compromise the thermodynamic stability of the pMHC complex itself. This finding reshapes understanding of HIV's evasion strategy, demonstrating that the virus exploits a mechanism distinct from canonical TCR antagonism and underscores the selective pressure imposed by high-affinity, broad-footprint TCRs during chronic infection.",
 "noncanonical": {
